\f0\fs28 \cf0 Democracy gives every citizen a share of power, but it does not give them a manual. Most people do not wake each morning thinking about constitutional design or institutional repair. They think about whether their families are safe, whether their children are learning, whether their communities feel whole, whether their work leads somewhere, whether their country still belongs to them, and whether the future will be better or worse than the present. The strength of a republic rests on the ability of ordinary citizens to connect those lived realities to the choices they make at the ballot box. Authoritarians rely on breaking that connection. They depend on distraction, polarization, selective memory, and the steady erosion of civic confidence. A healthy democracy depends on the opposite: clarity, coherence, and a shared language for naming what is harmed and what is repaired. This toolkit offers that language, not as a set of tactics but as a way of seeing power and responsibility in everyday life.\
